==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|匕|卩|ls=ic}}: a man standing and a man kneeling; compare {{zh-m|化}}, {{zh-m|比}}, {{zh-m|北}} and {{zh-m|尼}}.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=𠨐-ancient,卭,𭅵,夘,𨙪-erroneous}}
The sense “I” has been hypothesized to be from {{och-l|我|I}} (ultimately from {{der|zh|sit-pro|*ŋa}}) with an attached vocative suffix ''*-ŋ'' ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 1999: 134}}). However, evidence for the latter suffix is sparse; Sagart otherwise only adduces the pair of words {{och-l|女|woman}} and {{och-l|娘|mother (originally as a term of address)}}.

